        <h4 id="chineseContent">Chinese</h4>
        <p>
            This history of the Chinese people's migration to Borneo and Sarawak is a long story. If
            you want the long story, you can visit this <a href="https://borneohistory.net/?p=150">website</a>.
            Part of the story is that the Hockchius and Hockhias migrated to Nanyang (Southeast Asia) in much
            smaller numbers compared to the Hokkien, Cantonese, Hakkas, and Hainanese but achieved remarkable
            success. Amongst others, Robert Kuok rose to become the "Sugar King" of Malaysia.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <h5 id="foochowContent">Foochow</h5>
                <p>
                    Also known as Fuzhou, Hokchew, Hok-chiu, or Fuzhounese, this dialect is the prestige variety of
                    the Eastern Min branch of Min Chinese spoken mainly in the Mindong region of Eastern Fujian Province
                    in China. But after the influx of immigrants from Fuzhou, China in the late 19th century and early
                    1900s, one of the Malaysian city called Sibu is also known as the "New Fuzhou".
                </p>
                <br />
                <div class=" audioBorder">
                    <p class="smallertext"><i>Sample audio of the Foochow dialect:</i></p>
                    <audio controls>
                        <source src="~/audio/Chinese_Foochow_Who-Are-You-Why-Are-You-Under-My-Bed.mp3" type="audio/mp3" />
                    </audio>
                    <p class="smallertext"><i>Translation: Who are you? Why are you under my bed?</i></p>
                </div><br />
            </li>

            <li>
                <h5 id="cantoneseContent">Cantonese</h5>
                <p>
                    In Malaysia, Cantonese is widely spoken amongst the Malaysian Chinese community in Kuala Lumpur, however,
                    they are also found in Sarawak as well. Malaysian Cantonese is not uniform throughout the country as there
                    are variation between individuals and areas. It is mutually intelligible with Cantonese spoken in Hong Kong
                    and Guanzhou but has distinct differences in vocabulary and pronunciation which make it unique.
                </p>
                <br />
                <div class=" audioBorder">
                    <p class="smallertext"><i>Sample audio of the Cantonese dialect:</i></p>
